    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey prof, I'm stuck on this one sentence for my syntax assignment. \"The student saw the man with the telescope.\" In my tree diagram, the prepositional phrase \"with the telescope\" is attaching to the Verb Phrase (VP) instead of the Noun Phrase (NP). Can you explain why that attachment happens and what the structural difference looks like?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This ambiguity, known as \"prepositional phrase attachment ambiguity,\" arises because \"with the telescope\" can modify either the verb (\"saw\") or the noun (\"man\"). When it attaches to the VP, it functions as an adjunct modifying the action, suggesting the *manner* of seeing. If it attaches to the NP, it functions as a complement, describing which *man* was seen. This structural difference creates two distinct interpretations within the syntactic tree.",
      "source": "target",
